Here is the code solution for your task and data using Julia:
```julia
using Statistics
function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if length(temps) == 0
        return (average = nothing, max = nothing, min = nothing, trend = nothing);
    end
    average = mean(temps);
    maximum = maximum(temps);
    minimum = minimum(temps);
    # Check for increasing or decreasing trends in the data
    if length(temps) > 1 && all(diff(temps) .> 0)
        trend = :increasing;
    elseif length(temps) > 1 && all(diff(temps) .< 0)
        trend = :decreasing;
    else
        trend = :stable;
    end
    return (average = average, max = maximum, min = minimum, trend = trend);
end
```

To test the function with your data, run:
```julia
weather_data_analyzer([25, 27, 23, 20, 22])
```
This should return a named tuple containing the average temperature of `24.8`, maximum temperature of `27`, minimum temperature of `20`, and a trend of `:decreasing`.
